Segmentation¶

Segmentation is a common image processing task that results in object rather than image information. Segmentation can involve multiple filters and algorithms or can be as simple as thresholding the image and finding contiguous regions. In the following, we will look at a simple but common approach and then explore some more sophisticated image segmentation methods.

First, we again need modules for image import and plotting.

Let's go through our image processing steps so far.

  • First, let's gaussian blur the original image (here the DNA channel)
  • Then, let's apply the Otsu threshold to obtain a binary image.
  • Remove small holes and small objects.
  • Apply a morphological opening to separate touching cells.
In [4]:
Gauss = gaussian(channel_1, sigma=5)
Thresholded = Gauss > threshold_otsu(Gauss) 
Holes_removed = remove_small_holes(Thresholded, area_threshold = 512)
Small_objects_removed = remove_small_objects(Holes_removed, min_size = 1024)
Opened_binary = opening(Small_objects_removed, disk(13))

Let's have a look how the cells are labeled.

These functions find the boundaries in a binaray image, label individual contiguous regions, and generate overlay images for quick display. rescale_intensity is used to adjust the brightness of the original image.

As you can see, there are still many touching cells that are receiving the same label. Can we do better than that?

Watershed¶

The Watershed is a frequently used algorithm to separate touching objects. To apply Watershed in scikit-image, we need some more modules. Some of them are from the scipy library.

In [9]:
from scipy.ndimage.morphology import distance_transform_edt
from scipy import ndimage as ndi
from skimage.feature import peak_local_max
from skimage.segmentation import watershed

The Watershed is effective in separating objects but prone to over-segmentation. We need to give the algorithm some 'orientation'. Often, the distance transform is used to find markers for the Watershed. Execute the next cell to do the following:

  • Generate a distance transform image from the thresholded image.
  • Find local maxima and generate a marker image.
  • Run the watershed on the inverse distance transform -DT using our markers.

The result is a 'label' image where each identified object gets a different number.

In [10]:
DT = distance_transform_edt(Small_objects_removed)
Coords = peak_local_max(DT, labels=Small_objects_removed, min_distance=25) # adjust the minimum distance depending on cell size / pixel size
Mask = np.zeros(DT.shape, dtype=bool)
Mask[tuple(Coords.T)] = True
Mask = dilation(Mask, disk(5))
Markers, _ = ndi.label(Mask)
Labels = watershed(-DT, Markers, mask=Small_objects_removed)

For the Watershed algorithm, the distance transform serves as the 'catchment basins', which will be 'filled' after which the separating 'dams' are created. Here a look at the distance transformed image in 3D.

In [11]:
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D
In [46]:
DT_copy = DT
DT_copy[DT_copy < 0] = 0 # set negativce values to zero

ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, -DT_copy.astype(int), rstride=10, cstride=10, linewidth=0, cmap='gray')

This goes in the right direction! Now, more cells are separated. Another flavor of the Watershed uses a gradient filter to find the outline of cells and uses it as 'dams' for the algorithm. We will compare these flavors of Watershed and other segmentation approaches in the homework exercise.

Evaluating segmentation results¶

When setting up a new segmentation pipeline, it is important to test how good the segmentation is. This is frequently done with a 'ground truth', a segmentation that is considered optimal. A real ground truth can only be established from synthetic data - images that are artificially generated and then changed in a way that a microscope would (addition of simulated noise, aberrations etc.). If we want to obtain ground truth from real world images, the best we can often (unfortunately) only do is label the images by hand, i.e. draw regions around cells and mark them as 'foreground'.

Let's test the Watershed on an image where we drew some masks by hand, and compare to our manual segmentation.

In [20]:
test_image_files = sorted(glob('../evaluation_data/images/*.tiff'))
test_image = imread(test_image_files[0])
test_mask_files = sorted(glob('../evaluation_data/masks/*.tiff'))
test_mask = imread(test_mask_files[0])
In [38]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(20,10))
ax[0].imshow(test_image)
ax[0].axis('off')
ax[1].imshow(test_mask)
ax[1].axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()

Let's run the pipeline that we have so far.

In [39]:
Gauss = gaussian(test_image, sigma=5)
Thresholded = Gauss > threshold_otsu(Gauss) 
Holes_removed = remove_small_holes(Thresholded, area_threshold = 512)
Small_objects_removed = remove_small_objects(Holes_removed, min_size = 1024)
DT = distance_transform_edt(Small_objects_removed)
Coords = peak_local_max(DT, labels=Small_objects_removed, min_distance=25) # adjust the minimum distance depending on cell size / pixel size
Mask = np.zeros(DT.shape, dtype=bool)
Mask[tuple(Coords.T)] = True
Mask = dilation(Mask, disk(5))
Markers, _ = ndi.label(Mask)
Labels = watershed(-DT, Markers, mask=Small_objects_removed)

Let's compare the result to the manual annotation.

In [51]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(20,10))
ax[0].imshow(Labels, cmap='jet')
ax[0].axis('off')
ax[1].imshow(test_mask,  cmap='jet')
ax[1].axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()

We can see that the Watershed did well, but how well did it do? A measurement for that is the intersect over union (IOU).

In [34]:
result1 = Labels > 0
result2 = test_mask > 0
intersection = np.logical_and(result1, result2)
union = np.logical_or(result1, result2)
iou_score = np.sum(intersection) / np.sum(union)
In [37]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(20,10))
ax[0].imshow(intersection)
ax[0].axis('off')
ax[1].imshow(union)
ax[1].axis('off')
plt.tight_layout()
In [54]:
print("IOU score is {:4f}".format(iou_score))

IOU score is 0.860047

In this example, the Watershed did not detect some cells at the image border, but we still get a 86% overlap with the hand annotated image. Not bad for a (cumulative) few lines of code! However, this example was relatively 'easy' as the cells were nicely spaced and we would probably also get a good results by only thresholding the image.
